<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1912-03-06T23:36:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1912-03-06T23:36:00-05:00" n="965" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d965">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.00/3068.</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">American Ambassador</gloss> to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi>.</head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegrams.—Extracts.—Paraphrases.]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Mexico</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-03-06T22:00:00-06:36">
                                    <hi rend="italic">March 6, 1912—10 p.m.</hi>
                                </date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>The municipal council of Mexico City has issued a call to all friends of
                            order, foreign or native, to arm themselves for the purpose of assisting
                            the Government in maintaining order. I do not myself regard the danger
                            here as immediate or great, but precautionary measures may be wise in
                            preventing what many fear. I therefore intend taking the same action,
                            but more effectively, which the Department instructed me to take during
                            the revolution against General Díaz.<note n="1" xml:id="d965fn1">See
                                    <ref target="frus1911#pg_477">For. Rel. 1911, pp. 477</ref>,
                                    <ref target="frus1911#pg_479">479</ref>, <ref target="frus1911#pg_481">481</ref>, <ref target="frus1911#pg_489">489</ref>, <ref target="frus1911#pg_492">492</ref>–<ref target="frus1911#pg_493">493</ref>, <ref target="frus1911#pg_497">497</ref>–<ref target="frus1911#pg_498">498</ref>, <ref target="frus1911#pg_506">506</ref>.</note> In the discussion
                            with my European colleagues they expressed disapproval of the course of
                            our Government in permitting the shipment of arms and ammunition across
                            the frontier to the revolutionists.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Wilson</hi>.</signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>